---
import SocialList from "@/components/SocialList.astro";
import PostPreview from "@/components/blog/PostPreview.astro";
import { getAllPosts, sortMDByDate } from "@/data/post";
import PageLayout from "@/layouts/Base.astro";

const MAX_POSTS = 10;
const allPosts = await getAllPosts();
const allPostsByDate = sortMDByDate(allPosts).slice(0, MAX_POSTS);
---

<PageLayout meta={{ title: "Research" }}>
	<section class="mt-0git flex flex-col gap-8 sm:flex-row">
		<img
			src="/WEBSITE_MP.jpg"
			alt="Johann Ohler"
			class="w-full rounded-lg object-cover sm:w-1/5 lg:w-1/3"
		/>
		<div class="flex-1 text-justify leading-normal">
			<p class="mb-4">
				I am a first-year PhD Student in Economic History at the LSE. My research interests lie in <span
					class="decoration-3 font-bold underline decoration-accent">Economic History</span
				>, <span class="decoration-3 font-bold underline decoration-accent"
					>Population Economics</span
				> and <span class="decoration-3 font-bold underline decoration-accent"
					>Political Economy</span
				>. In my current projects I use large-scale data sources to better understand the economic
				and political factors that drove the demographic changes of the 18th and 19th century.

				<p class="mb-4">
					I am a member of the <a
						class="cactus-link"
						href="https://www.lse.ac.uk/Economic-History/HED"
						class="text-link hover:underline"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noopener noreferrer">Historical Economic Demography</a
					> group, and am supervised by <a
						href="https://www.ericbschneider.com/research"
						class="font-semibold text-link">Eric Schneider</a
					> and <a href="https://www.tomraster.com/" class="font-semibold text-link">Tom Raster</a>.
				</p>

				<p class="mb-4">
					You can find my CV <a
						href="https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ztlk7oyrptvgxp0ee0o8h/CV_Johann_Ohler.pdf?rlkey=u6ojvd4kihatugfrmisl6zpkm&st=64uwzjj5&dl=0"
						class="text-link">here</a
					>. Email: <a href="mailto:j.p.ohler@lse.ac.uk" class="text-link">j.p.ohler@lse.ac.uk</a>
				</p>
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="mt-16">
		<!-- Working Papers Section -->
		<h1 class="mb-2 text-lg font-bold">Working Papers</h1>
		<ul class="mb-8 space-y-4">
			<li>
				<strong>
					<a
						href="https://download.ssrn.com/yexeh/bc1a57b6-42a3-42d6-a1cf-22fa42e5c6c4-meca.pdf?response-content-disposition=inline&X-Amz-Security-Token=IQoJb3JpZ2luX2VjEFsaCXVzLWVhc3QtMSJHMEUCIAE99vOTXQXbZGTmPPCECcuLcD%2Fx0n8eyI4LMcMcAR0vAiEA8xPJGf3MO53LiV7pdeM8vGwcTLCcaNapPTrJ0rkzw3EqvQUIFBAEGgwzMDg0NzUzMDEyNTciDA9dZtb%2BaSsuqnDZjyqaBYa6Hmw3tA3cra8lPkyKmJvwr1P9NCRyES%2FBk6BNvDZoNdSBvT4vzA0J10PRofmwyhBJA89NXYU6cAt3BAc%2FpOSI%2ByoOmeBwo%2BYXoiHrWt69TBN0SG8yFkVqaMIOlWZkGb7FhC0jaeDQ%2FKJ27Ski8hkGefVXIJ%2B94DQLhz0PxoJVif9CjXoQK8wygpaSEZDR3bhDaADayVdpwlas2FeIq%2BHDcGFyo%2FOyW%2BgQN7iAfwHBEdxtPZdUut41AsPKiYhzVek1hlsa5i23YD6K11oVFOPZYmYU01aVh8VKV987flBiIgHKp%2BQ%2F%2FQggba%2BEXz7kCBBrKU2F34DDuTDyPJss1kbDzjZNO%2FVqXv6WxgYOguHnn49ZktXUqtXLvBZzgLRJvxq2SfNgYTCJlcwISNvhAT6%2BkNasQRcz%2B3S8omQAfQ%2Fz6o1ws2OVHcbOJea%2BEwH%2BSiUDWBxrvKwzpY6sG0q4UN2Yy1p0%2F%2BUUMLQirisqagRToP9R1O3Cl2mI9nUVDESnveymqP8Zz88MFf52esJkpX7Q9H14J2KVXhmMBRlznOy1ykMa%2FNlOnyF1ncJhA%2Bqg%2BF0EANm2FpSGchLrV9ux0YkZvsCW3tvfvhLE8DhC3eKz9YGq00Aw782M45RxXNw8KJPlb4BBJRqv%2F2MWPfYFsiO3WsDrS1XQpVGN%2FQ2SKd1Ma3iiV6RunG0vykKEaQoonVRLZk5rSEnkbmFju7qZkqRWkMhfiKu07dViwaGefqIFc0qX9978l%2Bcuml8C3psfetbXE3X7rA6U1euK0Qkn%2Bn%2BKMW7z6%2BZrUhdWmIMN%2Be%2FokcahOTnt2nKveNBz6gZsV6wTCfvehapJ%2FA4vtJJyaWKUfMYew0SivXnOGGeJkrOzUmsvGWjAeVef4DDZh8a6BjqxAVmy9bbTRXeBeZ8Kp5FHm9ASRqUD5tPN0NsvT4r%2FinR0fCdssPicdNUxawvSu2iUn59Xf4AqraGwGIGlMwFT8x8BrwW5EKYo9br%2Bg7mpVxsfaE%2BjatIj4z7Fup9QHZfa8FMbBMMJ0qIozYCxBK9V5G3s9EUehV3qwDee3mq9ybb6wLjDvm3qMn9VsXXmMAO82fPqzl3OrrZO4a0yJNmywxOpOlzeS6SYzq0aM4Ai%2F%2FdhbA%3D%3D&X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&X-Amz-Date=20241205T112504Z&X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host&X-Amz-Expires=300&X-Amz-Credential=ASIAUPUUPRWEUTHUN6YF%2F20241205%2Fus-east-1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request&X-Amz-Signature=70b43f5be8fa880783740f0ad3530b395094458adafb733b2f6061a1110242ca&abstractId=4965731"
						class="text-link"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noopener noreferrer"
						>Malthus in Germany? Reproductive Success and Status in pre-industrial Germany</a
					></strong
				>
				<!-- Presentation Section -->
				<p class="ml-4 mt-2 text-[1.2rem]">
					<span class="underline decoration-[var(--theme-quote)] decoration-2">Presentations:</span>
					IPECE (UCD), Centre for Economics, Polics, and History (TCD), Irish Economic Association Conference.
				</p>
				<!-- Awards Section -->
				<p class="ml-4 mt-2 text-[1.2rem]">
					<span class="underline decoration-[var(--theme-quote)] decoration-2">Awards:</span> LSE Economic
					History Best Dissertation (2023), Francesca Carnevali Prize (2024).
				</p>
				<!-- Abstract Section -->
				<p class="ml-4 mt-2 text-[1.2rem]">
					By exploiting the demographic records of 150,000 individuals from the historical county of
					Wittgenstein, I test for status gradients in child mortality (the Malthusian positive
					check) and marital fertility (preventive check). While I find no evidence for a status
					gradient in child mortality, I find strong evidence for a status gradient in fertility.
					The richest families had, on average, one-and-a-half extra children compared to their
					poorer compatriots. Turning to the mechanics of the preventive check, this was driven by
					delayed marriage in low-status families. Disaggregation of my dataset into six periods
					reveals that this fertility differential began to disintegrate around 1800.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
